 digitalWrite(GREEN, HIGH);
 digitalWrite(GREEN, HIGH);
 digitalWrite(YELLOW, LOW);
 digitalWrite(YELLOW, LOW);
 digitalWrite(RED, LOW);
 digitalWrite(RED, LOW);
 delay(5000); // Green for 5 seconds
 delay(5000); // Green for 5 seconds
 // Yellow on
 // Yellow on
 digitalWrite(GREEN, LOW);
 digitalWrite(GREEN, LOW);
 digitalWrite(YELLOW, HIGH);
 digitalWrite(YELLOW, HIGH);
 delay(2000); // Yellow for 2 seconds
 delay(2000); // Yellow for 2 seconds
 // Red on
 // Red on
 digitalWrite(YELLOW, LOW);
 digitalWrite(YELLOW, LOW);
 digitalWrite(RED, HIGH);
 digitalWrite(RED, HIGH);
 delay(5000); // Red for 5 seconds
 delay(5000); // Red for 5 seconds
}
}
Notes:

The function delay(ms)
pauses execution for ms
ms milliseconds. For example, delay(5000)
pauses for 5 seconds.
Pin numbers must match your wiring.

Step 5 — Upload the code to the Arduino

In Arduino IDE, select Tools > Board and choose your board (e.g., Arduino Uno).
Select Tools > Port and choose the correct COM/USB port.
Click the Upload button (right arrow). Wait until "Done uploading" appears.
Observe the LEDs cycle: green → yellow → red according to delays.
Step 6 — Test and adjust timing

If you want shorter or longer light durations, change the values in 
delay(...). Example: change delay(5000)
delay(5000) to delay(3000) for 3 seconds.
After editing, save and upload again.
Troubleshooting

No LEDs light: check that the Arduino is connected, pins match, and GND is connected.
LED always on: confirm the LED is connected to the correct pin through a resistor (not directly to 5V).
Upload errors: ensure the correct board and port are selected; close other programs using the same port.
Important Terms and Definitions

Arduino: A small microcontroller board used for running simple programs and controlling electronics.
C++ (Arduino sketch): The programming language and structure used to write code for Arduino; sketches include setup() and loop().
GitHub Desktop: A graphical app for cloning, committing, and managing GitHub repositories on your computer.
Repository (repo): A folder that contains project files and version history hosted on GitHub.
Clone: A local copy of a GitHub repository on your computer.
Commit: A saved change in the repository history.
Push / Pull: Sending (push) or retrieving (pull) commits between local and remote repositories.
LED: Light Emitting Diode, an electronic component that emits light when current flows.
Resistor: An electrical component that limits current to protect LEDs.
Digital pin: A numbered pin on Arduino used for input/output.
GND (Ground): The reference point in an electrical circuit; needed to complete the circuit.
delay(ms): Arduino function that pauses the program for the specified milliseconds.
Final tips

Save changes to D.Arduino-C++Tut in your local cloned folder before committing in GitHub Desktop.
Use GitHub Desktop to Commit and Push when you want your changes reflected in your fork on GitHub.
Keep the wiring neat and label pins so code and hardware match.
